    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>The festival of Mikong is the Kanakanavu people’s celebration of millet harvest in honor of their millet god, tamu vinaʉ. Today, the festival is held in October on an annual basis. The festival takes place after the millet harvest, proceeding from family prayers, making rice cakes (“pepe”), presenting offerings to the millet god to bidding farewell to the millet god. Once the family ritual is over, each family is to bring their home-made pepe, wine and fish to cakʉrʉ (“tribal meeting place”) to attend tribal worship.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>米貢祭為卡那卡那富族小米豐收與祭祀小米神tamu vinaʉ之儀式，現今多於十月左右舉辦。祭儀舉行於小米豐收後，先後包含家祭、製作小米黏糕、祭祀小米神、送小米神。儀式先以各家為舉行單位舉行家祭，各家代表再攜帶小米黏糕pepe、魚與酒到部落會所cakʉrʉ舉行團祭。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
